---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="FAQ">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

    <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.25rem;">

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Is neuroplastic pain real?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Yes, absolutely. Brain imaging (fMRI) shows the same pain-processing regions activate in neuroplastic pain as with physical injury. The pain is not "in your head" — it's in your nervous system. The difference is the cause (brain-generated versus tissue damage), not the experience.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">How do I know if MY pain is neuroplastic?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Key indicators: pain that persists after injuries should have healed, pain that moves or spreads, multiple conditions across body systems, stress making it worse, treatments targeting the body not helping, normal medical tests. Take the <a href="/quiz">self-assessment quiz</a> or review the <a href="/intro/symptoms">12-point checklist</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Can I have both structural AND neuroplastic pain?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Yes — this is common. You might have genuine arthritis or a herniated disc PLUS a sensitized nervous system that amplifies the pain far beyond what the structural issue explains. Brain-based treatments can still help significantly by addressing the neuroplastic amplification component. The question is not "is there anything on the MRI?" but rather "does what's on the MRI explain the severity of symptoms?"</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">What's the difference between PRT and Sarno's approach?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Same foundation, different execution. Sarno's approach was primarily educational — you read a book, attended a lecture, and thought psychologically when pain appeared. PRT adds structured techniques (somatic tracking, emotional processing, safety reappraisal) and has been validated in rigorous clinical trials. PRT systematizes what Sarno observed clinically.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Do I need a therapist to do PRT or Schubiner's program?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Not necessarily. Many people recover using Alan Gordon's book <em>The Way Out</em> or Schubiner's workbook. However, a trained PRT practitioner can accelerate progress, help with stuck points, and address underlying trauma. Group workshops are a middle ground — more structure than self-directed, less expensive than individual therapy. See the <a href="/resources">resources page</a> for directories.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">How long does recovery take?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">The PRT clinical trial showed 66% pain-free after 8 sessions over 4 weeks. Schubiner reports that many patients see significant shifts within 3-4 weeks of his program. However, recovery varies widely — some people feel better within days of understanding the diagnosis; others need months of consistent practice. Factors that influence speed: how long you've had pain, how much fear you hold, any unprocessed trauma, and how consistently you practice the techniques.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">What if I try PRT and it doesn't work?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">First, give it proper time — at least 4-6 weeks of consistent daily practice. If no progress: (1) Revisit the "personalized evidence" component — lack of conviction that your pain is neuroplastic is the most common barrier. (2) Consider whether there's unaddressed trauma or emotional material that needs EAET or trauma-informed therapy. (3) Check if you're using somatic tracking to "fix" pain rather than to experience safety — the paradox matters. (4) Some people have a purely structural cause for their pain and need different treatment. (5) Work with a trained PRT practitioner — self-directed recovery doesn't work for everyone.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Can children/teens have neuroplastic pain?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Yes. Schubiner has treated many adolescents with chronic pain, migraines, and other symptoms. A PRT workbook for teens was recently published. The mechanisms are the same — stress, pressure, perfectionism, and emotional factors create learned pain pathways at any age. Recovery is often faster in younger people due to greater neuroplasticity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">What's the connection between childhood experiences and chronic pain?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) are strongly linked to chronic pain in adulthood. Early adversity sensitizes the stress response system, making the nervous system more reactive throughout life. This isn't destiny — understanding the connection is the first step to rewiring. EAET and trauma-informed PRT specifically address this pathway.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Will I need to keep doing these techniques forever?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">No. The 5-year follow-up to the PRT trial showed that once the brain updates its pain predictions, the changes tend to stick. After recovery, most people use techniques only during occasional flare-ups — and those flares are shorter and less intense. The goal is cure, not management. However, the lifestyle changes (stress management, self-compassion, emotional awareness) that supported recovery tend to be beneficial to maintain.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Can exercise make neuroplastic pain worse?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">It can if done with fear. If you're bracing through exercise, expecting pain, and hyper-vigilant about sensations, you're reinforcing the threat signal. The key is pacing — staying within your window of tolerance while gradually expanding it. The brain needs experiences of safe movement to update its predictions. This is very different from "pushing through" pain, which typically worsens neuroplastic pain.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">What about diet, supplements, and alternative therapies?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">These can help indirectly — a healthy diet reduces inflammation, magnesium can aid sleep and muscle relaxation, omega-3s support nervous system health. But for neuroplastic pain specifically, they address symptoms rather than the core mechanism. The most effective treatments directly target the brain's pain processing. Use complementary approaches as supportive tools, not primary treatments.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">Is this approach compatible with other pain treatments?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Generally yes. PRT and Schubiner's method can be done alongside physical therapy, medication, and other treatments. The key distinction: treatments that target the body (stretching, massage, injections) may provide temporary relief but can also reinforce the belief that "something is wrong with the body." Brain-based treatments should be the core approach for neuroplastic pain, with other modalities as supportive adjuncts. Always coordinate with your healthcare team.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.05rem;">I've been in pain for decades. Is it too late?</h3>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">No. Neuroplasticity doesn't have an expiration date. The Boulder PRT study included patients with an average pain duration of 10 years — and they still achieved 66% pain-free rates. Schubiner has treated patients with 30+ years of chronic pain who recovered. The brain that learned pain decades ago can learn safety now. The mechanism is the same regardless of duration.</p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin-top: 2rem; background: var(--teal-light);">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <strong>Have a question not answered here?</strong> Explore the <a href="/intro/what-is">intro guides</a>,
        check the <a href="/glossary">glossary</a>, or dive into the
        <a href="/blog">research digest</a>. This site is continuously updated.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
